By Week 28, the story is less about a single shock than about a thickening atmosphere. The institutions of a constitutional republic are still present, still busy, still issuing rules and rulings. Yet more of this activity bends toward one center of power. Trade, welfare, immigration, information, even the shape of the White House itself are pulled into a single orbit. The week\'92s events show a government that has learned to use complexity as cover, emergency as routine, and law as a tool rather than a limit. That pattern holds the week together.\
\
The Democracy Clock reflects that tension between motion and constraint. It opened Week 28 at 7:58 p.m. and closed there as well. On its face, nothing changed. The hands did not move closer to midnight. But the stillness is deceptive. The clock held because the week mixed deep structural damage with pockets of resistance that, for now, kept the overall balance from tipping further. Courts blocked some of the harshest moves. States and cities carved out small zones of inclusion. Investigative reporting forced reversals. The net effect was stasis in time, not in power.\
\
The most visible shift came in how the administration treated economic facts themselves. When the July jobs report showed only 73,000 new jobs and a rising unemployment rate, the president did not argue with the analysis; he attacked the existence of the number. He called the report rigged and fired the Commissioner of Labor Statistics, Erika McEntarfer, replacing a career statistician with a political appointee. That act did not change a single job, but it changed who controls the story of the economy. It signaled that official data would be accepted only when it served the regime\'92s narrative. In a democracy, shared numbers are one of the last common languages. When they are brought under partisan control, public debate loses its ground.\
\
The same week, the administration moved to make emergency trade powers a permanent tool of domestic rule. A dense web of executive orders and tariff announcements turned the International Emergency Economic Powers Act into a standing trade statute. New tariffs hit European, Japanese, British, Brazilian, Indian, South Korean, Indonesian, Vietnamese, Pakistani, Philippine, and Canadian goods, often at double\uc0\u8209 digit or even 50% rates. One order suspended duty\u8209 free de minimis treatment for all countries, pulling even low\u8209 value imports into the tariff net. Another declared a national emergency over Brazil\'92s treatment of Jair Bolsonaro and imposed a 40% duty on selected Brazilian imports. A separate order raised tariffs on Canadian goods from 25% to 35%, citing fentanyl and Canada\'92s recognition of Palestine. These measures were framed as reciprocal or security\u8209 driven, but their pattern was political. Trade became a lever to reward or punish foreign governments for their alignment with the president\'92s preferences, not a policy debated and set by Congress.\
