Courts did not stand aside entirely. A federal appeals court heard challenges to the president\'92s use of IEEPA for \'93reciprocal\'94 tariffs, and small businesses and Democratic\uc0\u8209 led states pressed the case that such sweeping duties exceeded statutory authority. At the same time, another appeals court refused to lift an emergency pause on the administration\'92s attempt to end birthright citizenship, and a federal judge ordered the administration to continue Medicaid reimbursements to Planned Parenthood despite a tax\u8209 bill provision aimed at cutting them off. These rulings did not undo the tariff regime or the broader assault on reproductive care, but they showed that some judges still understood law as a limit, not a weapon. Their decisions slowed the advance of emergency powers even as the executive tried to normalize them.\
