Yet the judiciary itself was being reshaped to make such resistance less likely in the future. The Senate confirmed Emil Bove, a former Trump defense attorney and senior Justice Department official, to a lifetime seat on the federal appeals court by a 50\'9649 vote. Whistleblowers had accused Bove of urging DOJ lawyers to ignore court orders on migrant flights and of misleading Congress about dropping corruption charges against New York\'92s mayor. More than 80 judges and multiple former officials raised concerns about his fitness. The confirmation went through anyway, on party lines with two Republican defections. In parallel, the Justice Department filed a misconduct complaint against Judge James Boasberg for public comments critical of the administration, and federal criminal proceedings in New Jersey were halted amid questions about the legality of acting U.S. attorney Alina Habba\'92s appointment. The department quietly extended the terms of interim U.S. attorneys in Nevada and Los Angeles just before their statutory limits, blocking district judges from naming replacements. Together, these moves shifted the justice system\'92s center of gravity toward loyalists and sent a message to judges who might think of crossing the administration.\
